.TH FORMAT(1),User Commands,FORMAT(1)

.SH NAME
format - format a text document with justified paragraphs

.SH SYNOPSIS
format [-h] [file]

.SH DESCRIPTION
format reads file (or standard input if no file is given) and prints it as text flowed into paragraphs justified to the current terminal width.
Consecutive non-blank lines are combined into a single paragraph; blank lines separate paragraphs.
All but the last line of each paragraph have their words spaced apart to reach the full terminal width, and paragraphs are indented with a tab.

format also recognises a small subset of troff-style directives.
Any line beginning with a period is interpreted as a directive:

 .TH title,section,header: Print a centered title line with the given fields separated by commas.

 .SH heading: Print a section heading in plain text.

 .I heading: Print a section heading in inverted colors.

Other directives are a fatal error.
This makes format the renderer used by man(1) for cx16os man pages.

.SH OPTIONS
-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

.SH LIMITS
Lines longer than 256 characters are a fatal error.
The internal paragraph buffer holds 4096 bytes;
when full, format flushes the current paragraph and continues.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: File processed successfully.

1: File could not be opened, a line was too long, or an unknown directive was encountered.

.SH SEE ALSO
man(1)
